<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>1</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Further written evidence from Dave Holladay (CYS0102)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My name is Dave Holladay I have been involved in transport and cycling since the age of 12 when I began a delivery round using a bicycle, and riding widely around London &amp; Home Counties.  I have followed a career in engineering and transport, working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">variously for British Rail, Sustrans and CTC over a period of 38 years. I now work as an independent integrated transport specialist.  My main modes of transport are on foot, cycle, and train, although I have held a driving licence since 1970, and driven a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> variety of vehicles including motorcycles, and towed trailers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to my earlier submission I would like to highlight some other agencies whose approaches to crashes and incidents ijn places other then the workplace, and the agency charged with re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gulation of the use of large goods vehicles and the prevention of harm through that use..</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Government Agency which could ’prevent harm’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Traffic Commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> act as the regulators of both drivers and operators of the vehicles which you are investi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gating with regard to cyclist and pedestrian deaths and serious injuries.  The Commissioners have powers to revoke the vocational licences of drivers who fail the test of having good repute, and even enforcing a complete ban on driving. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However their abi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lity to gather and respond to the intelligence available is hampered by the lack of a formal conduit which can feed information on driver behaviour back to the Traffic Area Offices. Discussing this with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Nick Denton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Commissioner for the Metropolitan &amp; Sout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heastern Area) he highlighted that his Scottish counterpart </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Joan Aitken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> had a Memorandum of Understanding with Police Scotland to get all traffic offences committed by drivers with C, D, E licences reported automatically to her office. The English and Wels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h Commissioners are apparently unable to do likewise because of the 43 separate Police Authroities they need to get a common agreement with.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With such powers we might have saved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Catriona Patel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s life by removing the Class C licence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Denis Putz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a litany of driving bans and serious traffic offences to his name well before he killed her when driving drunk and using a mobile phone. We might even have picked up on the poor driving of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Darren Foster</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> before he killed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Hope Fennell </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and we hope that the r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">estoration of his C1 standard licence does not automatically see the C licence restored, without a formal review of his fitness to hold that class of licence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Commissioners can also call in operators who fail the conditions of good repute as well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the set criteria for management of their operations, if they get appropriate recognition and support in this work, but tellingly it is the restricted licence operators who are reported to be a prevailing feature of disciplinary hearings. These operators, c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arrying only their own goods, are exempt from the requirement to have a qualified transport manager, and various other provisions placed on domestic and international operators. Many waste management operators are operating with restricted licences, a deta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">il highlighted by Jack Semple of RHA in his evidence to the Committee. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are also vehicles which weigh up to 40 tons that require no operator’s licence nor a driver with more than a car licence, and have no limits on drivers hours. many are classed a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s ’plant’ and can often be used on the road with duty-exempt ’red’ diesel. An example is here http://www.utranazz.com/Portals/0/files/Kimera-K55-batching-plant-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">brochure.pdf .   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I believe that it would be useful to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">call in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and hear from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Traffic Commis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">sioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on how they can act to regulate the use of HGV’s and deliver their objective to ’prevent harm’ from the operation of commercial vehicles.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Investigation of Rail Crashes (Rail Accident Investigation Branch). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This system delivers an non judgement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al report, which is transparently available in the public domain. The reports list the sequence of events, and their outcomes, and quantify the details of the vehicles, and people involved and the various site measurements, followed by an analysis of the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ausal factors and hazards relating to the incident, concluding with a list of recommendations to prevent a recurrence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It doesn’t always deliver perfectly – notably the issue of single lead junctions, where a crash at Bellgrove in Glasgow was followed 2 y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ears later by a similar crash at Newton before the need to provide a more positive measures, or eliminate the arrangement at the junctions where it had been designed in.  However the road crash equivalent is just not of a matching standard.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A road crash m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ay be investigated by Police or an Insurer but these reports are not automatically published, and will generally have the objective of identifying one or more of the parties involved in the crash as being liable for prosecution or providing recompense to o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thers who suffer loss or injury.  There is no clear setting out of the hazard(s) at the root of the crash, and the risk management (or failure of the risk management systems) that played their part in the crash under investigation. There is no clearly spel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led out action to prevent recurrence of the same type of crash, which a roads authority should consider for implementation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a result of this even a brief trawl of incidents that were known to me, over the past 13 years, brought up 2 examples of where a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> basic hazard as not been eliminated, and risk management regimes are clearly inadequate</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Example 1) the left turn from the offside lane across ALL traffic travelling in the nearside lane – from a brief check in minimal detail 5 identical circumstances whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re for keeping speed up or the basic lack of space the truck or bus/coach driver has made a left turn from a traffic lane designated for vehicles travelling straight ahead. In only one case I have checked was action taken to remove the hazard (Ellie Carey </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– killed December 2011, and as a result, HGV left turns banned between Tower Bridge Road and Abbey Street)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of the 6 deaths in November both Richard Muzira and Francis Golding died when a truck driver approached the junction in an offside lane and cut across the nearside lane, more tellingly, the death of Francis Golding was a repeat of the death of Wan-Chen McG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uinness almost exactly 5 years earlier with a large truck making the same left turn from Vernon Place in to Southampton Row from a lane over to the right hand side – signed for travelling straight ahead. Two fatalities, and potentially other near misses I’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve yet to uncover shout that the large vehicles should not be permitted to make left turns at this junction, in its present layout.  Large vehicles should be sent round via High Holborn, where the space to make wider turns is available, make their Northbou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd turn at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tottenham Court Road, or the junction made suitable for large vehicles turning from the left turn lane.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This hazard exists at many junctions across London, and the move for improving cyclist and pedestrian safety has to be a review of places </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where the potential hazard exists, and a risk management plan for each individual location drawing on known crash reports, the conditions in which large vehicles attempt this manoeuvre, and the practical options for modifying the junction geometry, or dive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rting left turning large vehicles via a safer route. I would also hope that delivery of published crash investigation reports would  highlight those locations where the greatest risk and greatest urgency for action exists in this respect.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Example 2) Bo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w roundabout. An analysis of the hazards on the CS2 route here will show that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">100% of the motor vehicle traffic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> circulating on this roundabout </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WILL drive through the path of any cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> using CS2 as this traffic joins or leaves the A12. From observation a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">round 80%, and possibly more of the motor traffic travelling on the East-West axis uses the roundabout to join or leave the A12.  Managing the risk of this motor traffic colliding with a cyclist relies entirely on the human factor detail of compliance with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the instructions given by traffic signs and signals.  There is no fail to safe position whereby the failure to observe a signal or sign by either a driver or cyclist does not create an inevitable crash, or near miss incident.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By contrast TfL’s own survey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> shows that around 60% of the cycle traffic actually goes over the flyover where there is almost a 0% potential for the hazard of a motor vehicle turning through the path taken by a cyclist. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The type of report required is very much set to the same templa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">te as used by RAIB, and HSE, for dangerous and fatal incidents where the locations are on the railway or the workplace.  HSE has for over a decade been highlighting the flawed situation where the employer and employee’s duties of care at work vanish when t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he workplace is on the public road.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The HSE work notes that at least a third of road crash KSI’s are liked to use of the road as a workplace and this figure is around 10% of their annual reported KSI at work incidents.  This makes the road an area where H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SE wants to deliver the safety improvements delivered on construction sites and in factories by their regime.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With TfL committing almost £1bn to cycling I suggest that  a budget be included in this to deliver published and impartial investigation repo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rts into fatal and serious cyclist and pedestrian crashes, and draw on those reports to inform and deliver on effective design which;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">       identifies the hazards, </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">       eliminates those hazards where possible</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">       provides an effective risk manageme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt regime when the hazards cannot be    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">       completely eliminated</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To inform the Committee I would suggest that a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">representative from HSE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> describes their work on management of road risks in their efforts to get the safety culture of the workplace extended to embrace the use of the road as a workplace. Failing the HSE the RAIB could be invited to describe how their regime can be applied to r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oad crashes and dangerous incidents.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Truck design </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent CLoCS event had an example of a tipper truck with a low level driving position which gives direct vision between those outside and inside the cab. Not only does it enhance the safety of cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and pedestrians, but also the safety of drivers – falls from trucks with high cabs are a major source of driver injury – A PQ on this might be very informative. TfLcould introduce a requirement for such cab designs with a 5 year horizon in exactly the sam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e way as they already have done for emissions, and low floor accessible buses.  Mercedes and Dennis Eagle are supplying such vehicles, and they are discussing the wider adoption of low cab designs for urban trucks with SMMT and TfL. It would be useful to h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ave such input to the Inquiry·</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Truck definition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – there are vehicles which look to all intents like trucks, can weigh the maximum permitted weight of a truck and yet be driven with no operators licence, by a driver with Class C1 (standard driving licence)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and no drivers hours regulation. the Committee should be aware of vehicles such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mobile </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Volumetric </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Batching </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Plant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which have been noted to be pulled over at up to 25% overweight for the chassis they are being used on.  At the same time a major legislati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve change could have serious impact on specialist firms operating such vehicles and plant in a responsible way within the current system.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Reducing ton miles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Concrete mixer trucks travel relatively short distances, but tippers are often doing 70+ mile round trips and this activity cannot be shut down. Some machinery – like Tunnel Boring Machines could seize in the bore if they stop moving forward. and produce t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onnages that should be put on rail or water – we have NO serious strategy to provide railheads and wharves, and instances of promised alternatives have failed to be delivered because the co-ordination cannot be delivered for the sporadic demands of individ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ual developments. TfL say that they cannot, as a public body underwrite or operate such a transfer/consolidation  facility with public funds but we have the conundrum of being able to maintain such a facility for a few £’000 per year and the very unlikely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">position that a £2-£3m facility taking 2-3 years to deliver would be viable for each new project.  Reducing ton miles reduces risk, reduces pollution, reduces road damage. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inviting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TfL Freight Unit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may be a useful way to give an insight into describing h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ow large volumes of building materials could be moved other than by road or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lynch of Brentwood</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who are already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">removing up to 500 trucks per day</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from the roads by using the river and canals in London.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Rail Freight Group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can equally describe how their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">facilities already reduce the number of truck trips and ton miles to depots like that at St Pancras. They can describe what is possible now and the issues which are limiting their ability to move more by rail or river, which are I believe a major stumbling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> block in reducing the number of large trucks moving around in London.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">December 2013</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Droid Sans'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>